<Layout title="Fake WAP">
  <Rounded>
    <div class="content">
      <h1>Fake WAP:</h1>
      <br />
      <h3>
        Fake WAP stands for Fake Wireless Access Point, which is a type of cyber
        attack where an attacker sets up a fraudulent wireless access point to
        trick unsuspecting users into connecting to it. The attacker can then
        intercept and potentially steal sensitive information, such as login
        credentials, credit card numbers, or other personal data, that the user
        sends over the fake access point.<br /><br />

        In a Fake WAP attack, the attacker typically uses a portable Wi-Fi
        router or a smartphone with a mobile hotspot to set up a fraudulent
        wireless access point. They then give the access point a name that is
        similar to a legitimate network, such as a coffee shop's Wi-Fi or a
        hotel's guest network, to make it appear trustworthy to lure
        unsuspecting users into connecting to it.<br /><br />

        Once the user connects to the fake access point, the attacker can
        intercept any data that is sent over the connection. This can include
        login credentials, credit card information, browsing history, and other
        sensitive data. The attacker can then use this information for malicious
        purposes, such as stealing the user's identity, conducting financial
        fraud, or launching further attacks.<br /><br />

        One of the most concerning aspects of Fake WAP attacks is that users
        often have no idea they have been compromised. The attacker may be able
        to intercept their data without the user realizing anything is wrong.
        This is why it's important to take steps to protect yourself when using
        public Wi-Fi networks.<br /><br />

        To prevent Fake WAP attacks, here are some best practices you can
        follow:

        <ol>
          <li>
            Always verify the name and legitimacy of the network before
            connecting to it. Check with the establishment or venue to make sure
            you're connecting to the correct Wi-Fi network.
          </li>
          <li>
            Use a virtual private network (VPN) to encrypt your internet traffic
            and protect your data. A VPN creates a secure, encrypted tunnel
            between your device and the internet, making it much more difficult
            for attackers to intercept your data.
          </li>
          <li>
            Avoid accessing sensitive information, such as banking or credit
            card information, while connected to public Wi-Fi networks. If you
            must access sensitive information, consider using your mobile data
            connection instead.
          </li>
        </ol>
        <br />
        By following these best practices, you can greatly reduce your risk of falling
        victim to a Fake WAP attack and protect your personal and sensitive data.
      </h3>
    </div>
    <br />
